aries of the “Free World” and elevated the United States as the central actor in Cold War geopolitics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aCold War. 0aPresidentszUnited StatesxInfluence. 0aRhetoricxPolitical aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / General.2bisacsh  aUS presidential rhetoric, US foreign policy, global rhetorical presidency, Cold War, Harry S. Truman, Dwight D. Eisenhower, John F. Kennedy, Richard Nixon, Ronald Reagan.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076650940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226823645423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226823645/original  a978-3-11-076650-9  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles